WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.000
African safari won, breakfast time.

00:05.000 --> 00:08.000
It is very early in the morning.

00:08.000 --> 00:14.000
Adam and Lily are going on safari in Kenya.

00:14.000 --> 00:20.000
Their friend Joseph is waiting for them.

00:20.000 --> 00:26.000
Look Adam, I can see him.

00:26.000 --> 00:33.000
The airplane is arriving at a small airport in the Masai Mara.

00:33.000 --> 00:37.000
Joseph is standing near his jeep.

00:37.000 --> 00:41.000
He works in the game reserve.

00:41.000 --> 00:52.000
Today he is meeting Adam, Lily and some American visitors.

00:52.000 --> 01:00.000
The friends say hello and get into the jeep.

01:00.000 --> 01:07.000
This is Anne. Behind her are Jeff and his son Tom.

01:07.000 --> 01:12.000
Hi, is this your first safari?

01:12.000 --> 01:16.000
Yes, I can't wait.

01:16.000 --> 01:20.000
I know that face.

01:20.000 --> 01:23.000
Tom wants to see the big five.

01:23.000 --> 01:28.000
Yes, look, I've got a book about them.

01:28.000 --> 01:36.000
That woman is very quiet. Who eats sheep?

01:36.000 --> 01:45.000
Hey, listen, can you hear that? A lion? Quick, let's go.

01:45.000 --> 01:59.000
Joseph drives the jeep across the country.

01:59.000 --> 02:02.000
Look, Zebra for breakfast.

02:02.000 --> 02:13.000
Quiet, Jeff. You don't see this very often.

02:13.000 --> 02:21.000
Zoe, Lily's friend is at home in London.

02:21.000 --> 02:26.000
Look, Dan, this is from Lily.

02:26.000 --> 02:29.000
Is she in Africa now?

02:29.000 --> 02:33.000
Yes, she is. Listen.

02:33.000 --> 02:39.000
Hi, Zoe. We arrived in Kenya yesterday.

02:39.000 --> 02:43.000
Now we're on safari.

02:43.000 --> 02:49.000
In the Masai Mara, Joseph is with us.

02:49.000 --> 02:57.000
He was Adam's student in Nairobi. He's a driver now.

02:57.000 --> 03:01.000
There are three Americans in our jeep.

03:01.000 --> 03:05.000
I'm sending you some photos.

03:05.000 --> 03:10.000
The woman doesn't smile or talk to us.

03:10.000 --> 03:13.000
We were lucky this morning.

03:13.000 --> 03:20.000
A lion had a Zebra for breakfast in front of our jeep.

03:20.000 --> 03:26.000
I've got about 100 photos of it.

03:26.000 --> 03:31.000
It's okay. There was no danger.

03:31.000 --> 03:36.000
Tomorrow, we're going to get up at five.

03:36.000 --> 03:41.000
We want to see some elephants.

03:41.000 --> 03:50.000
Dan, I know that woman in the hat, but I can't remember her name.

03:50.000 --> 03:53.000
Do you know?

03:53.000 --> 04:00.000
Let's see the photos.

04:00.000 --> 04:03.000
The big five.

04:03.000 --> 04:06.000
Joseph loves his job.

04:06.000 --> 04:11.000
The day starts very early at five o'clock.

04:11.000 --> 04:17.000
Every day, he drives visitors across the Masai Mara.

04:17.000 --> 04:21.000
Often, breakfast is in the jeep.

04:21.000 --> 04:27.000
They stop near the river Mara and watch the hippos.

04:27.000 --> 04:31.000
They see the giraffes in the trees.

04:31.000 --> 04:37.000
Families of zebras are eating grass.

04:37.000 --> 04:44.000
Then, Joseph and his visitors look for the big five.

04:44.000 --> 04:50.000
The big five are big, strong animals.

04:50.000 --> 04:56.000
They are lions, leopards, elephants,

04:56.000 --> 05:00.000
buffaloes, and rhinoceroses.

05:00.000 --> 05:05.000
They are all very dangerous.

05:05.000 --> 05:14.000
Lions and leopards usually hunt for food at night and sleep in the day.

05:14.000 --> 05:20.000
Lions hunt and kill big animals.

05:20.000 --> 05:28.000
They eat giraffes, zebras, and other big five animals.

05:28.000 --> 05:36.000
Leopards eat meat, too, but they like to eat small animals.

05:36.000 --> 05:39.000
First, they kill them.

05:39.000 --> 05:45.000
Then, they often take the dead animals up into the trees.

05:45.000 --> 05:49.000
There, they eat them slowly.

05:49.000 --> 05:53.000
Buffaloes live in big groups.

05:53.000 --> 05:58.000
They are very strong, and they can kill a lion.

05:58.000 --> 06:05.000
They eat green food, tall grass, and other plants.

06:05.000 --> 06:11.000
They like the rain, and they like to be near water.

06:11.000 --> 06:16.000
They live for about 17 years.

06:16.000 --> 06:20.000
Rhinos are endangered animals.

06:20.000 --> 06:27.000
There are only about 40 black rhinos in the Masai Mara today.

06:27.000 --> 06:32.000
Some people hunt rhinos because of their horns.

06:32.000 --> 06:39.000
In some countries, people give a lot of money for a rhino horn.

06:39.000 --> 06:42.000
This is a big problem.

06:42.000 --> 06:48.000
The police and the keepers want to stop them, but that is difficult.

06:48.000 --> 06:54.000
Rhinos eat grass and fruit, but no meat.

06:54.000 --> 06:56.000
They sleep in the day.

06:56.000 --> 07:00.000
Sometimes, they sleep on their feet.

07:00.000 --> 07:05.000
Elephants live in big family groups.

07:05.000 --> 07:07.000
They don't eat meat.

07:07.000 --> 07:13.000
They only eat trees, plants, and fruit.

07:13.000 --> 07:20.000
They are very intelligent, and they can understand other elephants.

07:20.000 --> 07:28.000
They make noises, but people can't always hear them.

07:28.000 --> 07:39.000
African safari too, a long afternoon.

07:39.000 --> 07:43.000
The jeep stops near a river.

07:43.000 --> 07:47.000
Look, hippos!

07:47.000 --> 07:51.000
Wait! I'm coming!

07:51.000 --> 07:57.000
Lily, that woman's name is Ruth Street.

07:57.000 --> 08:02.000
She's American, but she lives in London.

08:02.000 --> 08:06.000
Her photo was in the newspapers yesterday.

08:06.000 --> 08:10.000
The police are looking for her.

08:10.000 --> 08:15.000
She buys rhino horns for a group in the...

08:20.000 --> 08:23.000
Look at that mouth!

08:23.000 --> 08:26.000
He wants to eat your bag, Lily.

08:26.000 --> 08:28.000
No, he doesn't.

08:28.000 --> 08:32.000
Look, buffaloes!

08:32.000 --> 08:35.000
But where are the elephants?

08:35.000 --> 08:40.000
We're going to find them now, Tom.

08:42.000 --> 08:46.000
Let's go. It's going to rain.

08:46.000 --> 08:50.000
Yes, please. Let's go.

08:50.000 --> 08:55.000
Suddenly, it was dark, and the rain started.

08:56.000 --> 09:01.000
I'm going to stop. I can't see.

09:01.000 --> 09:06.000
I don't like this.

09:06.000 --> 09:09.000
Is that an elephant?

09:09.000 --> 09:14.000
Yes, the mother's behind him.

09:14.000 --> 09:17.000
Lily wants to adopt an elephant.

09:17.000 --> 09:19.000
Lily?

09:19.000 --> 09:22.000
Excuse me. Oh, yes.

09:22.000 --> 09:27.000
I want to visit the elephant orphanage.

09:27.000 --> 09:34.000
Good. Ah, the rain's stopping. Let's go.

09:38.000 --> 09:41.000
Look at this, Adam.

09:41.000 --> 09:46.000
Oh, Lily. Is it from Zoe?

09:47.000 --> 09:51.000
Adopt an elephant.

09:51.000 --> 09:54.000
This is Shukuru.

09:54.000 --> 09:57.000
She is from Sarvo.

09:57.000 --> 10:04.000
Today, she lives in the Sheldrick Elephant orphanage near Nairobi.

10:04.000 --> 10:10.000
She arrived at the orphanage in September 2009.

10:10.000 --> 10:14.000
She was only three days old.

10:14.000 --> 10:19.000
Now she has a new family and a lot of friends.

10:19.000 --> 10:22.000
Visitors can meet her.

10:22.000 --> 10:29.000
They can adopt her too, but she is always going to live in Africa.

10:29.000 --> 10:33.000
A lot of people visit the orphanage.

10:33.000 --> 10:40.000
At 11 o'clock in the morning, the elephants come out with their keepers.

10:40.000 --> 10:44.000
The elephants run and play.

10:44.000 --> 10:48.000
Then the keepers give them their food.

10:48.000 --> 10:54.000
Sometimes a young rhino comes out and plays too.

10:54.000 --> 11:02.000
The visitors stand very near the animals and take a lot of photos.

11:02.000 --> 11:09.000
The animals are in the orphanage because they haven't got families.

11:09.000 --> 11:13.000
The keepers are their mothers.

11:13.000 --> 11:24.000
After some time, perhaps ten years, the elephants go back into the wild.

11:24.000 --> 11:27.000
Samson's story.

11:27.000 --> 11:31.000
The year was 1954.

11:31.000 --> 11:36.000
There was very little rain in the Sarvo game reserve.

11:36.000 --> 11:40.000
Some visitors arrived and they loved Sarvo.

11:40.000 --> 11:45.000
One evening, they watched a family of elephants.

11:45.000 --> 11:51.000
One young elephant was very thin and unhappy.

11:51.000 --> 11:55.000
He was ill and he wanted water.

11:55.000 --> 11:59.000
He walked slowly behind his mother.

11:59.000 --> 12:05.000
The elephants arrived at the water and started to drink.

12:05.000 --> 12:10.000
The young elephant wanted to stay near the water.

12:10.000 --> 12:13.000
His mother wanted to go.

12:13.000 --> 12:22.000
She didn't want to go away from her son, but she went with the other elephants.

12:22.000 --> 12:26.000
The visitors watched the young elephant.

12:26.000 --> 12:28.000
He was lucky.

12:28.000 --> 12:33.000
No lions or other animals came near him.

12:33.000 --> 12:40.000
The elephant was the first orphan in David Sheldrick's elephant orphanage.

12:40.000 --> 12:46.000
His name was Samson.

12:46.000 --> 12:49.000
African Safari 3.

12:49.000 --> 12:52.000
Where is Anne?

12:52.000 --> 12:56.000
I don't like that girl.

12:56.000 --> 13:01.000
She's always looking at me.

13:01.000 --> 13:05.000
The police are looking for you.

13:05.000 --> 13:09.000
Go away for a week or two.

13:09.000 --> 13:16.000
Go on Safari or to the desert.

13:16.000 --> 13:18.000
Where's Anne this morning?

13:18.000 --> 13:21.000
She wasn't at breakfast.

13:21.000 --> 13:23.000
We can't wait.

13:23.000 --> 13:27.000
We're going to see the rhinos this morning.

13:27.000 --> 13:30.000
Okay, let's go.

13:43.000 --> 13:45.000
Can we get out?

13:45.000 --> 13:50.000
Yes, the keepers are always near them.

13:50.000 --> 13:56.000
Lily looks at the rhinos and thinks about Anne.

13:56.000 --> 13:59.000
Smile, Tom.

13:59.000 --> 14:02.000
Jeff is smiling too.

14:02.000 --> 14:08.000
He's got photos of four of the big five.

14:08.000 --> 14:12.000
Thanks, Joseph. That was a beautiful day.

14:12.000 --> 14:18.000
Lipids tomorrow, Tom. And Masai dancing this evening.

14:18.000 --> 14:22.000
Adam, let's find Anne.

14:26.000 --> 14:31.000
She isn't here and her things aren't here.

14:31.000 --> 14:39.000
Where is she?

14:39.000 --> 14:42.000
The Masai people.

14:42.000 --> 14:46.000
The Masai are very interesting people.

14:46.000 --> 14:53.000
Many live in Kenya near the Masai Mara game reserve.

14:53.000 --> 14:58.000
The men and the women are tall and strong.

14:58.000 --> 15:06.000
Every day they walk across the country with their cows and their goats.

15:06.000 --> 15:13.000
There is very little grass in the Masai Mara and very little rain.

15:13.000 --> 15:21.000
The men and boys hunt wild animals and bring them back home.

15:21.000 --> 15:26.000
Sometimes very young boys kill lions.

15:26.000 --> 15:32.000
This is dangerous, but for the Masai it is important.

15:32.000 --> 15:38.000
The Masai dress in beautiful colors, usually red.

15:38.000 --> 15:41.000
They like dancing and singing.

15:41.000 --> 15:50.000
Sometimes they sing and dance for visitors at the hotels in the game reserve.

15:50.000 --> 15:55.000
Masai women don't hunt, but they do a lot of work.

15:55.000 --> 15:59.000
They build the houses for their families.

15:59.000 --> 16:09.000
The Masai people move from place to place and the women build new homes in the new places.

16:09.000 --> 16:17.000
Every morning they get up very early and bring water for their families.

16:17.000 --> 16:25.000
This is a very important job because water is a big problem for the Masai.

16:25.000 --> 16:28.000
The women make the food too.

16:28.000 --> 16:34.000
The Masai eat meat and they eat food from plants.

16:34.000 --> 16:38.000
Not all Masai children go to school.

16:38.000 --> 16:43.000
Often there are no schools near their homes.

16:43.000 --> 16:50.000
School is expensive too and many families haven't got the money.

16:50.000 --> 16:56.000
Today many Masai people live and work in towns.

16:56.000 --> 17:04.000
Sometimes they visit their families and friends.

17:04.000 --> 17:12.000
African Safari 4, a good day for rhinos.

17:12.000 --> 17:16.000
Your taxi is coming now Miss Wilson.

17:16.000 --> 17:18.000
Thank you.

17:18.000 --> 17:21.000
Okay, thank you.

17:21.000 --> 17:24.000
Yes, I understand.

17:27.000 --> 17:29.000
Hello Anne.

17:29.000 --> 17:32.000
Or is it Ruth?

17:32.000 --> 17:34.000
You again?

17:34.000 --> 17:35.000
Yes.

17:35.000 --> 17:39.000
And this time you are coming with us.

17:40.000 --> 17:42.000
What are they doing?

17:42.000 --> 17:48.000
Her name is Ruth Street. They are taking her away.

17:48.000 --> 17:53.000
Are you Lily? Zoe Brewster's friend?

17:53.000 --> 17:57.000
Miss Brewster telephoned our office.

17:57.000 --> 18:02.000
Look at this from 2010.

18:02.000 --> 18:06.000
Ruth Street is doing it again.

18:06.000 --> 18:10.000
Stop Ruth Street.

18:10.000 --> 18:17.000
Police are hunting for street in an expensive hotel near a game reserve.

18:17.000 --> 18:23.000
She is buying rhino horn and taking it back to Europe.

18:23.000 --> 18:27.000
There she is going to sell it on.

18:27.000 --> 18:32.000
Is there a problem? That's Anne.

18:32.000 --> 18:35.000
It's a long story, Jeff.

18:35.000 --> 18:39.000
Yes. Let's go and have a drink.

18:39.000 --> 18:41.000
Excuse me.

18:41.000 --> 18:46.000
This is from the hotel for all of you.

18:46.000 --> 18:50.000
Breakfast with the big five.

18:50.000 --> 18:53.000
Five o'clock start.

18:53.000 --> 18:57.000
Groups of five or six people.

18:57.000 --> 18:59.000
Thank you.

18:59.000 --> 19:04.000
Tom, we're all going to see leopards tomorrow.

19:05.000 --> 19:08.000
And rhinos.

